Problem:
68-year-old male presents to ED with acute onset chest pain radiating to left arm, associated with diaphoresis, nausea, and shortness of breath. Symptoms began 2 hours prior to arrival. Patient has history of hypertension and hyperlipidemia. Initial ECG shows ST-segment elevation in leads II, III, and aVF consistent with inferior STEMI. Troponin I elevated at 15.2 ng/mL (normal <0.04). Patient is hemodynamically unstable with blood pressure 85/50 mmHg and requires immediate intervention.
Goal:
Provide emergent cardiac catheterization and percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) for acute ST-elevation myocardial infarction. Stabilize hemodynamics, prevent further myocardial damage, and initiate appropriate post-MI medical management including dual antiplatelet therapy, beta-blockers, ACE inhibitors, and statin therapy. Monitor for complications including arrhythmias, heart failure, and mechanical complications of MI.
Outcome:
Patient admitted to Cardiac Intensive Care Unit for acute STEMI requiring emergent cardiac catheterization. Cardiology consulted and patient taken emergently to cardiac catheterization laboratory. Given severity of presentation, hemodynamic instability, and need for ongoing cardiac monitoring and intervention, patient meets criteria for inpatient admission. Anticipated length of stay 3-5 days pending procedural results and clinical stability. I had the pleasure of seeing John Doe in the University Vein Center today. John is a pleasant 49 y.o. male with a history of symptomatic venous reflux involving the bilateral lower extremities. On 2/28/2025, John underwent radiofrequency ablation of the left great saphenous vein, which was performed by Dr. Jane. John presents today for routine follow-up. Subjective: Since the procedure, John reports experiencing much improvement in prior symptoms of venous reflux. He denies any new leg swelling or pain, there is some tenderness and erythema at the proximal thigh without severe discomforts. There are no reported symptoms concerning for access site paresthesias. He reports consistent wear of thigh high compression, as previously directed. Overall, John is pleased with the outcome of the procedure. John denies any changes to health history, medications, or drug allergies since the last visit. Postoperative Diagnosis: Same as preoperative diagnosis Procedure: RFA of RIGHT great saphenous vein Procedure start time:1:29 Procedure end time:1:44 Indications: Marc P Doe is a 75 y.o. male who presented with signs and symptoms of bilateral lower extremity venous insufficiency. Venous competency duplex confirmed the diagnosis. Treatment was indicated. The patient was informed of the potential risks, complications, benefits and alternatives to the procedure including but not limited to bleeding, infection, DVT, and continued medical management. The patient acknowledged understanding and informed consent was obtained. Procedure: The patient was placed on the procedure table in a supine position. The right lower extremity was prepped and draped in the usual sterile fashion. A 2 patient identifier time out was performed. Under direct ultrasound guidance, the right great saphenous vein was accessed with an arterial entry needle at the level of the calf. A wire was advanced without difficulty. A small incision was made and the needle was exchanged out for a 7F sheath. The radiofrequency ablation probe was advanced to the level of the sapheno-femoral junction and was placed 3.8 cm from the epigastric. Tumescent solution was injected along the length of the vein under ultrasound guidance. The probe was activated and the vein was ablated. Sterile dressing was placed with Steri-strips, guaze and tegederm. The patient tolerated the procedure well. Post-procedure ultrasound documented patent common femoral and epigastric veins. All sponge and instrument counts were correct at the end of the case. I, Jane Dane, MD , was present for the entirety of the procedure. guidelines.report:
Hemodynamic Instability - Systolic BP
This criterion is met. The document states the patient is "hemodynamically unstable with blood pressure 85/50 mmHg". A systolic blood pressure of 85 mmHg is less than the guideline's threshold of <90 mmHg. While the document does not explicitly state "unresponsive to fluid resuscitation", the overall context of emergent intervention for acute STEMI and explicit mention of hemodynamic instability strongly indicates this criterion is satisfied.

Acute Coronary Syndrome (ACS) or Myocardial Injury - Biomarkers
This criterion is met. The document states "Troponin I elevated at 15.2 ng/mL (normal <0.04)". This value is significantly greater than the 99th percentile upper reference limit (URL) of 0.04 ng/mL and also more than 2x URL (0.08 ng/mL), confirming a high-risk myocardial injury consistent with the guideline. The document does not explicitly state a "rising pattern" but the acute presentation with a markedly elevated troponin is indicative of acute myocardial injury.

intensity_of_service_report.intensity_of_service_explanation: The patient is admitted to the Cardiac Intensive Care Unit (CICU) for an acute ST-elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI) and requires emergent cardiac catheterization and percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI). The patient is hemodynamically unstable, necessitating immediate intervention and stabilization. The planned PCI is listed as an inpatient-only procedure on the CMS list, and the overall clinical picture, including CICU admission and hemodynamic instability, strongly indicates the need for the highest level of care.
